    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If these irregularities have recently begun to appear and were not an issue before, there could be several reasons for the sudden change:\n\n1. Update/Change in Data Source: The logs might have undergone an unintended transformation due to changes in the data collection or generation process, processing steps, or transmission patterns.\n\n2. Environmental Changes: Changes in the environment where logs are generated, like updates to logging libraries, or system configurations, can introduce these irregularities.\n\n3. Corrupted or Interfered Data: There could be instances where the data is getting corrupted post-collection, perhaps due to network issues during transmission or intermediaries modifying the data.\n\n4. Insider Errors: Human error, whether in data entry, script modifications, or system administration, could also result in such patterns.\n\n5. Security Breach: Less likely but still possible, an attack like a Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) operation could manipulate the logs.\n\nInvestigate recent changes in your data flow, update logs, and security systems. Correlate this with spikes in irregular characters to isolate the cause. This will help you understand if you need strict input validation patterns in your parser or if it's a more complex problem related to your data pipeline.",
